The paper focuses on identifying and categorizing non-technical skills and abilities needed for software engineering, which falls under the software engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The paper also mentions the importance of adjusting training programs, which could fall under the human-computer interaction (cs.HC) or computer-supported cooperative work (cs.CY) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the opinions of technical experts, business experts, and academics, which could fall under the computer education (cs.EDU) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the gap between the industry and academic world, which could fall under the computer engineering (cs.CE) sub-category.
